  abstract = {The most important aspect of kant's critique of Judgment is that aesthetic judgments, or judgments of taste or judgments of the beautiful are universal, although they are subjective. The basis of the universality is not concept, for  what base aesthetic judgments are feelings. Therefore it is the "free play" or so called "harmony" of imagination and undestanding on which the aesthetic judgment depends on, as explained in § 9 of the Third Critique. Now the cheif actor appears on the scene. Kant argues that it could not be the case that the feeling is unconditioned and might be communicated subsequently. For if so, then the feeling would be private, which makes the saying that others ought to feel the same impossible. Therefore, it must be that universal communicability is the condition of possibility of aesthetic judgments. (p.1251) And the universal communicability is defined as the attunement of the faculties (Stimmung der Erkenntniskräfte).
Kant's contemporary, Schiller, in his On the Aesthetic Education of Man uses the term Stimmung to signify the aesthetic dsiposition, is a medium through which our mind passes from sensation to thought, and which is neither physical nor logical, but in which sense (Sinnlichkeit) and reason (Vernunft) are both active in both physical and logical ways at the same time. (Schiller 1982,151)
Entering the early 20th century, Stimmung transformed into a psychological concept which might be projected into objects (empathy) while only snetient beings emotions and moods. 
Two decades later, Heidegger showed up and gave an argument against the theory of projection: if the attribution of boredom to the book were only a projection of my mood, it would be incomprehensible how different objects can be perceived differently while being in the same mood. (1995, 82–88)
One of  Other approaches is Georg Simmel's. In“Philosophy of landscape” (1913), Georg Simmel examines landscape as an object of art, a totality which could not be divided into seperate parts, as more general nature. Stimmung of human is not itself something discrete, and in the same way, the stimmung of a landscape permeates all its components and therefore constitutes the unity of the landscape.
The view that Stimmung is a whole is proposed by Heidegger. Stimmung is, by Heidegger, constitutive of being-in-the-world as a whole. Moreover, it is a relational whole, in terms of being-withone-another (intersubjectivity) and in terms of being-amidst entities. (Heidegger 1996, cha.5, 126–31)

Gerhard Thonhauser. Beyond Mood and Atmosphere: a Conceptual History
of the Term Stimmung. Philosophia (2021) 49:1247–1265},
